🎬Imagine if you got a text from your ex six months after it was sent…and you got it on Valentine’s Day!💔

That is the premise of my romcom screenplay Best Before. It’s a combination of Love Actually, Sex and the City and The Wedding Singer. But with unexpected twists and my unique sense of humour.

Producers are showing interest in this script, which has been called “hilarious” and brilliant,” and The Ticket has been optioned to be a feature film or show! (Emphasis on has been -it’s available again, such a long story, I hear some films take 20 years to make!)

I can’t believe I have gone from being afraid to call myself a poet and writer in my 20s to now being able to say “I’m meeting with a producer about my work.” 

What a wild ride! It just shows that you have to keep believing in your writing and never give up on it. It might take three decades to realize your dreams. But we have one life to live, so keep writing if you love it and don’t be afraid to call yourself a writer, because Hollywood wants and needs more storytellers!

It’s not easy to explain my process, because it’s always changing, but one constant for my poems, novels and screenplays is that it begins with a scribbled idea in my current hard-covered poetry journal. Often full sentences get scratched out as I gather thoughts and try to find a better way of saying what I want to say. Only I can decipher the handwriting a week later—my good handwriting is reserved for my gratitude journals.

Once I’ve scribbled the beginnings of a poem, I move to my computer in my home office. Always, no exceptions. I need to type it and rework it -no music to change my internal rhythm and hopefully no distractions.

For novels and screenplays, I take cue cards and start plotting using my magnetic board.

But it all starts with a scribble.

What about you?

My insta might be pretty, but my days are full of highs and lows. My fortune cookie for the last six weeks likely read: The ship of life rarely sails on serene waters. 

I snapped the #1 and sleek hair, but don’t often capture photos of the lows —I’m either ugly crying or in a dumb argument with the love of my life and not about to grab a camera—but they are always there-without them life would not be real life. It wouldn’t even be like my fictional worlds, because as a writer I try to present the dark sides of love and life in my poems and novels. You laugh harder and smile longer at good jokes and sexy scenes if you have recently gotten yourself or someone you love up off on the ground, and you’re bloody, tired and about to quit.

I’m not just talking about the characters here. Art and life imitate one another.

A good haircut and a sweet poem by a warm fire won’t fix your life, but it might make you smile again, and that’s a start.

My week’s been precariously hovering between “ordinary day in Hill Valley,” and “when this baby gets to #1, you’re gonna see some serious shit.”

I am grateful, confused, make that constantly confused about this weird industry called fiction books, and tired. But not from the dancing, that was rejuvenating. 

I’m ready for the “serious shit,” have been for five years, but who knows what’s going to get hot and what will stay in the barn, being treated like an alien. 

OK it was a fun metaphor and it looks like I’m running with it. 

I just figured out what it feels like to be an indie author: like you’re an out of work actor, scraping the bottom of your savings jar, trying to come up with enough money so that you can get “fancy head shots,” because you’re told those head shots are exactly what you need to catch your big break.

Every day feels like that. Every day feels like a huge gamble. I can’t think of a day these last five years when I felt sure about a book marketing decision.

The writing part? That’s felt like a walk in fresh spring air after being stuck inside all weekend. 

It’s that love of writing that keeps me going—and like Marty needing to get back to 1985, no matter what is thrown at me in whatever year, I won’t give that up.

I’m tired of being told by movies, TV, streaming services and social media every single day that I need to cover up or drastically slow down my natural aging process. 

I’m wearing these reading glasses not because they look nice (my teen said I look “kinda nerdy” so I bought them—lately I do the opposite of what they say🤪) but because my prescription progressives aren’t quite strong enough anymore to see close up in the bathroom mirror just how badly I applied my eyeliner and mascara. Or to pull out that one white eyebrow hair I found the other day.😳It’s pathetic—because more are on the way. I’ll probably get new progressives…these work for the mirror and reading my phone, for now.

When did we stop listening to our bodies and start listening to what people trying to sell us expensive stuff said about our bodies?

It took five years for me to find a stylist who wouldn’t yell at me when I mentioned blending blonde highlights with my natural greying roots to look more my age. Yes, they all outright dismissed me: “you can’t do that!” until this most recent one (thank you for really listening Vivian).

I absolutely love makeup-free days and not using any filters on my selfies. But I keep finding, “you need foundation, mascara and lipstick at the very least!” As the theme on the top articles on that subject. 

If you’re in or nearing your 50s, you have earned the right to do more of what you want and love. You. No one else. 

Remember that young kid inside you who was excited to be one year older and have a big ol gap in your front teeth because you lost them naturally? Stop trying to hide any aspect of your beautiful, natural self! 

Now, I need to reread what I am about to post. Where the heck are my reading glasses?

DON’T CHASE A CHECKMARK
Guess what the most common question in my social media inbox is? No it is not “where can I buy your books?” although I do get that one, thank goodness. The most common question is: “how can I get a blue checkmark like you did?” and “how can I get 40,000 Meta-followers, because I can’t seem to get enough fans and I want more!”

The question, when it first came, took me aback. Don’t people know that those achievements come from hard work? From a lot of writing being published over 25 years in my case, and a lot of marketing trial and error and engaging daily with followers for over eight years?

I never asked for that checkmark. I never expected to have this many followers; when I reached 300 my first year on Facebook I was ecstatic. I’m a person who loves her alone time, and as a child, my family will tell you that I even had a little speech impediment (mostly a lisp). I had to work through that so I could one day speak and read my poems in front of crowds.

I’m grateful for all of you follower-friends because you brighten my day, but the attention can be daunting. I manage all my pages myself, and it does get to be overwhelming and, sometimes, a little creepy. 

If I had to do it all again, would I still do it? Sure. But maybe I wouldn’t take it so seriously. Maybe I wouldn’t spend hours a day on social media. Maybe I wouldn’t even squeal the morning I saw that blue checkmark. 

Don’t chase that blue checkmark. 100 years from now, our phones will be incinerated in a pile of garbage sent to outer space. Whatever is stored on them and how many followers you had in 2023 won’t matter.

Don’t chase that blue checkmark. Chase your toddler until his giggling becomes infectious; chase your dreams, sunsets, rainbows, and that last Mars bar in your kids’ Halloween candy; chase your dog in the yard, your cookies with a tall glass of milk; chase your whisky with ginger. Most of all, chase away hate and fear and welcome love into every corner of your life with an open mind and grateful heart. #authorlife #Canadians #publishing #bookish #socialmedia #fameisfleeting #fame #influencers #romancebooks #success #popularity #impact #growth

The Paradoxical Commandments
by Dr. Kent M. Keith

People are illogical, unreasonable, and self-centered.
Love them anyway.
If you do good, people will accuse you of selfish ulterior motives.
Do good anyway.
If you are successful, you win false friends and true enemies.
Succeed anyway.
The good you do today will be forgotten tomorrow.
Do good anyway.
Honesty and frankness make you vulnerable.
Be honest and frank anyway.
The biggest men and women with the biggest ideas can be shot down
by the smallest men and women with the smallest minds.
Think big anyway.
People favor underdogs but follow only top dogs.
Fight for a few underdogs anyway.
What you spend years building may be destroyed overnight.
Build anyway.
People really need help but may attack you if you do help them.
Help people anyway.
Give the world the best you have and you’ll get kicked in the teeth.
Give the world the best you have anyway.
by Kent M. Keith, 1968

I call this hairstyle “just go with it!” -which has also been my mantra for 2023. 

I’ve been praying the first few lines of the Serenity prayer every morning for the last few years. I wouldn’t say I’m religious; I’m spiritual, and this “prayer” —origins thought to be Sanskrit, or Aristotle—reminds me to find within myself the “serenity to accept the things I cannot change.” 

 I’d say it’s the most powerful lesson of my life thus far. I’m not a control freak but I definitely have big plans and expectations for myself and when those fall apart, which they often do, I’ve always been hard on myself. 

By learning to let things (and people) happen or not happen in my life, without forcing anything, I’ve found a sense of inner calm and more joy…most days. 🤪

I was usually picked last or second last in gym class for any team sport. I got below average times in sprints. I was the kid who could read well, but did all the dodging in dodge ball. 

I did manage to become a good endurance runner by grade seven. I could keep up with the leader of the pack. While I never won a local event, I held my own and finished my distance runs strong. I noticed after a few races how the early sprinters always lost steam and determination and fell behind. 

I’m glad I learned the importance of endurance at that young age. It’s served me well as a writer and owner of my own business. It’s far too easy to burn out and lose motivation when we try to do everything all at once, and quickly. 

It took me 10 years of regular yoga practice to achieve balance, and in my 9th year as a novelist and script writer, I’m finally realizing that endurance and balance are the key to long term success. 

Do I stumble? You bet—in my yoga practice and in my writing and publishing career. But I can’t keep learning and growing if I don’t at least try new techniques. So I try things a new way, fail bigtime, laugh at myself (after a good cry and some dark chocolate) and keep on going. 

The writing life is a marathon, not a sprint. Keep putting one foot in front of the other. Wear supportive sneakers, and don’t forget to enjoy the view.

RECIPE (makes 4 cocktails) 

5 cups diced watermelon, divided. Can be frozen to be more refreshing, but purée it with 4 tablespoons water so it’s like a slushie.

6 ounces gin, divided

8 tablespoons lime juice, divided

1 ⅓ cups diet tonic water, divided

3 teaspoons of honey (I use half a  teaspoon per glass if making individually)

Lemon wedges, for garnish

Purée the water garnishes. Add the honey and lime juice. Set this aside for any virgin cocktails. 

For 4 alcoholic beverages, spoon some purée into each glass, add the diet tonic water and 1.5 ounces of gin per glass.

I like to add a frozen wedge of watermelon or a frozen blackberry as an ice cube.

Lauren from Last Night is another “life is stranger than fiction” Love Again Series novel, inspired by a Canadian news story that went international. It is the novel I am most proud of writing. It’s not as funny (though there is amusing banter) or as steamy, and it touches on heavier topics like terrorism, sexual assault, transsexualism,and xenophobia (all of which we live on a daily basis in 2023!) because I wanted to make the themes not only about finding love in an unexpected place, but also about learning to accept and even love people who are different from you - be it their gender, sexuality, race or religion.

 When Sam meets Lauren in an off-campus basement bar, sparks fly, but when he tries to get her number the next day, he learns she's given him the wrong digits. Instead of feeling slighted, he has faith it's an honest mistake and worries she'll think he's "that guy" if he doesn't call. Without her last name or residence floor, he tries the university's email system, and mass-emails all 246 women named Lauren in hopes of finding the right one. The women bond in same-name solidarity, forming a Facebook group called Lauren from Last Night. When the story goes viral, the women promise to protect Lauren from "stalkerish" Sam, but they might be keeping her from the love of her life. "The Laurens" aren't the only obstacles in love's way. Sam and Lauren are both trying to escape their heartbreaking, tragic past.

Is love strong enough to lift us from the pain and prejudices that weigh us down? Read Sam and Lauren's page-turning story to find out.

Do you talk to strangers? We are told as children not to, but some of the best experiences in my life happened because I reached out and spoke to a stranger. 

I met Moha on the sidewalk of Ste. Catherine Street because she was dragging a tiny suitcase behind her and I joked, “I wish I could pack like you.” She laughed, and we kept walking and talking until we felt compelled to stop walking, moved to the side and continued our memorable conversation for 15 minutes. The reason I had to get to know her was that at the start of our conversation she said, “I hope that you’re having a nice life.”

Who says that? Moha does! I wish more people said that instead of “have a nice day.” She tells me she says it because it sparks meaningful conversations. We shared the surface stuff, then went beyond to our challenges and heartaches, and before we knew it we were teary eyed and hugging and encouraging one another.

I hope that you’re having a nice life, and that you meet kind strangers who become friends.

I started in my late 30s, took a break from when I had a baby at 33, and returned to it regularly in 2019. It’s been so helpful with symptoms of menopause -holy smokes Batman, can we talk about that?

😭Migraines. Mood swings. Weight redistribution in your body that feels out of control no matter how careful you are with fat and sugar in your diet. Restless legs, extreme fatigue, changes in vision, brain fog, oh and depression, that was sudden and unexpected. 

🧘🏼‍♀️Yoga is the only time during my day just for me. I can lose myself in my breath and poses. It’s challenging, but you don’t have to be perfect. You just have to show up and try to stretch a little farther than you did last time. And breathe a little deeper.

💪It makes you stronger, more balanced, more relaxed, and my thinking is always clearer and more focused after a practice. There are loads of free classes on social media and YouTube, but I love the online ones offered by #Modoyoga because I can fit them into my work schedule perfectly. If you have any questions about yoga, please drop me a comment! Happy to encourage you to try a form of exercise that’s changed my life in increasingly positive ways.

How do I love him? Let me count the ways. Not too happy about the driving with one hand, but a baby bird’s life was at stake, and my husband is a much better driver than me under pressure. We didn’t have a chance to put this bird in a box; something caught in its mouth? And we didn’t think we should switch hands and frighten him more, and needed every second we had to get it to the fabulous @lenichoir bird hospital -which stayed open 45 minutes late just for us!

Yes, Bill has shades of sexy, smart ornithologist Tripp Wilson; he’s also a little Pete McCarney and a lot of Mason Ellis (mmmm sandwiches). For all of my novels, of course I get inspiration from our romance, and then sprinkle pieces from other romances I’ve heard about and several interesting people I’ve met to form what are called composite characters.

We won’t know how this little guy fared until tomorrow, but no matter what happens my heart is full with love for my family who dropped everything to help out a wounded Sparrow.

Update on the little House Sparrow we found dazed under our bird feeder: thanks to the amazing volunteers and workers at @lenichoir it is on oxygen and medication to reduce swelling. It’s doing okay! 

They think it hit something hard—probably a window although we usually hear that sound and we didn’t. It was probably out of hiding for a little bit at our feeder so that it could get some food. The reason why we thought something was in its open beak is that it was mouth breathing because it was having problems getting oxygen. 

They told us we can call in two weeks to see how it’s doing. How wonderful that the doctors and volunteers at Le Nichoir will be taking care of it all that time and helping heal this little sparrow before they set it free in the wild again.

If you are able, they can always use donations. I have known this bird conservation place for 20 years. They provide proper care and treatment for injured or orphaned wild birds and release them back into their natural habitat. Wonderful people and truly an integral part of our nature loving community.

My bestselling book and scripts are set in the USA. All the rest of my novels and my poems have Canadian content. I decided that I wanted to represent the country that made me who I am in my literary work; however, they have proven not as sellable commercially as the works set in USA towns. I’m not giving in yet. I’m tired of watching movies obviously filmed in Ontario or B.C. that pretend to be an American town, or reading about beaches and lakes there when ours are just as stunning. I have nothing against you Americans -in fact many of my friends live in the US and 92 percent! of my book sales are from your country! So am I going down the least lucrative path by writing Canadian? I don’t know, but it’s something I feel called to do. I’m not guided by financial prospects when I write anymore. So expect Canadian characters, settings, wildlife and humour in my books. This HGS era is me being my most authentic self. Let’s go.

It will feel rough at first, but you can train yourself to wake early by drinking a glass of water before bed like I do (so you have to get up first thing in the morning) and setting your alert to gradually wake you 15 minutes earlier each day. There are also many cool apps that monitor your REM cycles and wake you up in between them so that you have a better chance of feeling more awake when your alarm clock sounds.

Love has kept us together. I have always believed it takes a village of family and friends to help your marriage navigate all you have to through the years. 🤣 I have been real with you aspiring authors from the very beginning. This is a great life, but it doesn’t always make a great living. I think a lot of us get caught up in the idea of how landing a book deal will make us rich like JK Rowling, Colleen Hoover or EL James. The reality is, the odds of getting a book deal right now are between 1% and 2% which is why so many authors are turning to self publishing. So now the self publishing market is saturated, and the chances of becoming a bestseller have lowered greatly since I started publishing in 2015. It isn’t impossible, but you need to know, your lifestyle is not going to be the Kardashian lifestyle, unless you are both very talented, hardworking, and, in my opinion, a little lucky. I was eying a gold Christmas dress recently and realized it makes much more sense to get a new sweatshirt, since I am practically always at my desk. 
But, let’s say you do get a book deal. The average advance is anywhere from $5000-$100,000, with many publishers now offering more royalties and a smaller advance. Also, the average book, traditional or self published, makes $300 in its lifetime. Yes $300 you heard that right! 
So, I beg you to only go into this if you love writing, and you think you can handle all of the marketing and advertising involved. You will need to be willing to learn new skills every year. And I beg you, never, ever pay money to get published! A reputable publisher will pay you an advance and cover all publishing costs.

I made this as a gift for every one of you. It’s my mission to make you laugh daily, but I also want to encourage you to realize that dream you think is too unreachable to even consider. 

It’s not. You started thinking small because society likes to tell us what we are capable of from the first day we arrive here (at least they’ve stopped telling girls they can only be nurses or teachers…we have made minute improvements). 

Think big and don’t listen to the naysayers. I quit a contract editing job years ago, saying I wanted to write books. The editor I was giving my two week’s notice to said, “Sure, lots of people say they’d like to write a book, but few ever actually do it.” I said, but I will, and he just smiled. 

A year later my first poetry collection came out and sold very well for an indie book, charting on Amazon in five countries. I landed traditional publishers for my next poetry books and novels and even learned how to write screenplays along the way, and 21 books later I am grateful for my career and relieved I never listened to that editor who underestimated me. 
 
We have one life. Just one. Figure out how to do the thing you’ve been dreaming about. Start today.

Ten years ago, a small Canadian publisher wrote me back a “Yes.” Yes, we will publish your fantasy romance story (magical realism wasn’t a term yet!) - and my career changed forever. I’m so thankful to them!

No longer did I have time to write or edit for national magazines(I miss it sometimes, but when one door closes…), I became a full time author in 2014, eventually turning to self publishing in 2016.

I haven’t looked back much—as hard as it is, I try to live in the present moment. But the present is so different from the early Kindle boom days! I’m happy I was part of the early boom for self-published authors, and excited about the future. I now have six novels and trad published audiobooks out, and the audiobook industry is rapidly growing. I’m also fascinated with the rise of book-to-film adaptations, and I’ve said it before and will say it again here: hologram books /video books are in the near (2030) future. We won’t have to hold our books - they will be displayed right in front of our eyes. 

I’m keeping my fingers typing and my mind open. It’s going to be one Strangely, Incredibly Good ride!
